      "content": "Protest tactics like sit-ins and boycotts were the most effective because they directly challenged the moral legitimacy of segregation, forcing the government to confront the reality that its laws were unjust. While they did cause immediate backlash and violence, this resistance was the catalyst that made the movement necessary and ensured that the resulting legislation would be deeply rooted in public support rather than just legal compliance. Without the intense pressure from these confrontations, the federal government would have had no incentive to pass the Civil Rights Act of 1964.",
